0","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Haroldston West, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Haroldston West, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"en":{"1270–":"1270–Deceased","1270–Male":"1270–Deceased","1272–Male":"1272–Deceased","1270–Female":"1270–Deceased","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","1250–Female":"1250–Deceased","1269":"1269","1300":"1300","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1270":"1270","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Haroldston West, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Haroldston West, Pembrokeshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Harold","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Harold</i> (Old Norse <i>Haraldr</i>, borrowed from an ancient Germanic form <i>Harjawald</i>). Alternatively, the name may arise from the Middle English personal name <i>Harwold</i>, <i>Harold</i> (Old English <i>Hereweald</i>), particularly in Suffolk, where there was also post-medieval confusion with   Hurrell  . These all go back to an ancient Germanic personal name composed of the elements <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>wald</i> ‘rule’, which is attested in Europe from an early date; the Roman historian Tacitus records a certain <i>Cariovalda</i>, chief of the ancient Germanic tribe of the Batavi, as early as the 1st century  AD  See also   Herald  .","English: habitational name from Harrold (Bedfordshire), from Old English <i>hār</i> ‘gray’ + <i>wald</i> ‘large tract of woodland, high woodland’.","Irish: this name is of direct Norse origin (see 1 above), but is also occasionally a variant of   Harrell   and   Hurrell  . Spellings without final <i>d</i> have been adopted as the Anglicized form of the Gaelic <i>Ó hEarghail</i> (see   Harrell  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Airoldi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Chantal, Germaine, Herve, Marcel, Rosaire.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the old personal name <i>Airoldo</i>, a variant of <i>Aroldo</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Hariwald</i>, composed of the elements <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>wald</i> ‘power, authority’; see   Harold  . This surname is also found in France, but to French Canada it was nevertheless brought from Italy."]},{"name":"Haroldson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Helmer.","Americanized form of Norwegian <b>Haraldsen</b> and Swedish <b>Haraldsson</b>: patronymic from the personal name <i>Harald</i>, Old Norse <i>Haraldr</i> (see   Harold  ). Compare   Haraldson   and   Haroldsen  ."]},{"name":"Harreld","meanings":["English: variant of   Harold  ."]},{"name":"Harrod","meanings":["English: variant of   Harold  . Compare   Herod  ."]},{"name":"Hurrell","meanings":["English: nickname presumably for someone with shaggy or unkempt hair, from a diminutive of Old French <i>hure</i> ‘hair’.","Irish (Antrim): possibly an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEarghail</b> ‘descendant of <i>Earghal</i>’, a variant of <b>Fearghal</b> (see   Farrell  ,   Arrell  , and   Harrell  )."]},{"name":"Haraldson","meanings":["Americanized form (and a rare Swedish variant) of Swedish <b>Haraldsson</b>: patronymic from the personal name <i>Harald</i>, Old Norse <i>Haraldr</i> (see   Harold  ). This is also an Americanized form of the Norwegian cognate <b>Haraldsen</b>. Compare   Haralson  ,   Haroldsen  ,   Haroldson  , and   Harrelson  ."]},{"name":"Harrold","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant of   Harold  ."]},{"name":"Harral","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Harold  ."]},{"name":"Harrell","meanings":["English: variant of   Harold  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEarghail</b> ‘descendant of <i>Earghal</i>’, a variant of the personal name <i>Fearghal</i> (see   Farrell  )."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Harold was born in 1270, in Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Richard Harold, I, was 20 and his mother, Isabel Martin, was 20. He had at least 1 son with Alice Dowston."},"et":{"1270–":"1270–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1272–Male":"1272–Surnud","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1269":"1269","1300":"1300","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1270":"1270","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Haroldston West, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Haroldston West, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1270–":"1270–Kuollut","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1272–Male":"1272–Kuollut","1270–Female":"1270–Kuollut","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1250–Female":"1250–Kuollut","1269":"1269","1300":"1300","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1270":"1270","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Haroldston West, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Haroldston West, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"fr":{"1270–":"1270–Décédé","1270–Male":"1270–Décédé","1272–Male":"1272–Décédé","1270–Female":"1270–Décédée","1300–Male":"1300–Décédé","1250–Male":"1250–Décédé","1250–Female":"1250–Décédée","1269":"1269","1300":"1300","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1270":"1270","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","Haroldston West, Pembr